Reasoning: 

1. cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) - The paper discusses the use of cellular radios by college-age students and their communication styles, which falls under the domain of human-computer interaction. 
2. cs.CY (Computers and Society) - The study explores the social implications of using push-to-talk cellular radios, which is relevant to the sub-category of computers and society. 
3. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) - The paper discusses the communication patterns and styles of the participants, which can be analyzed using social network analysis techniques. 
4. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) - This sub-category is less likely, but the paper may touch upon the computational complexity of implementing push-to-talk cellular radios. 
5. cs.MM (Multimedia) - The paper discusses the use of audio communication and intermittent conversation, which falls under the domain of multimedia.
